---
import PortalLayout from '../../layouts/PortalLayout.astro'
---

<PortalLayout
  title="Pedagogy — Sohma Institute"
  description="Why the Institute teaches the way it does. Case-based architecture, inverse classroom, portfolio assessment, and the clinical training pipeline."
>
  <article class="pedagogy-page">

    <!-- HEADER -->
    <header class="ped-header">
      <div class="section-label">Pedagogical Framework</div>
      <h1 class="page-title">How and why we teach differently</h1>
      <p class="page-intro">The Institute's pedagogical model is not a preference. It is a methodological commitment derived from the nature of the interventions being taught. Complex, multi-component therapeutic systems cannot be learned through lectures and examinations. They are learned through mentored clinical practice, case-based reasoning, and reflective portfolio development.</p>
    </header>


    <!-- OPENING POSITION -->
    <section class="ped-section" id="opening">
      <h2>The rejection of the lecture-hall model</h2>
      <p>The standard health education model fills auditoriums with students, delivers didactic content through lectures, and assesses competency through written examinations. This model was designed for isolated pharmacological agents with linear dose-response relationships. It fails catastrophically when applied to complex, multi-constituent interventions that operate across multiple biological systems simultaneously.</p>
      <p>The Institute inverts this model entirely. All didactic content is delivered asynchronously — self-paced, on the student's own schedule. Every hour of synchronous contact time is reserved for the work that actually requires a clinician in the room: supervised clinical practice, case-based reasoning, and peer conferencing.</p>
      <p>This is not a cost-saving measure. It is the only honest pedagogical approach for the complexity of what we teach.</p>
    </section>


    <!-- CASE-BASED ARCHITECTURE -->
    <section class="ped-section" id="case-based">
      <div class="ped-section-label">Commitment I</div>
      <h2>Case-Based Architecture</h2>
      <p>Every unit of competency at every tier is assessed through real clinical cases drawn from the Sohma House patient population. Not simulated cases. Not hypothetical scenarios. Real patients with real complexity, real comorbidities, and real treatment responses.</p>

      <div class="ped-detail-grid">
        <div class="ped-detail">
          <h3>Why real cases</h3>
          <p>Simulated scenarios cannot replicate the complexity of multi-system presentations. A simulated case of menopausal symptoms might include hot flashes, sleep disruption, and mood changes. A real case includes those plus a 15-year history of SSRI use, unresolved childhood trauma presenting somatically, three previous practitioners who failed, and a patient who has lost trust in the therapeutic relationship. You cannot simulate that. You can only learn from it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ped-detail">
          <h3>Supervision intensity</h3>
          <p>Clinical case exposure is calibrated to credential level. Tier 1 students observe and document. Tier 2 students assess and formulate under direct supervision. Tier 3 students manage cases with consultative supervision. Fellows operate with peer review. The scaffolding matches the competency.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ped-detail">
          <h3>Case documentation</h3>
          <p>Every clinical encounter is documented in the student's portfolio. Assessment, formulation, intervention plan, outcomes, and reflective commentary. This documentation is both the assessment instrument and the beginning of a lifelong professional development record.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- INVERSE CLASSROOM -->
    <section class="ped-section" id="inverse-classroom">
      <div class="ped-section-label">Commitment II</div>
      <h2>Inverse Classroom</h2>
      <p>The economic and pedagogical logic is identical: clinician time is the most expensive and most valuable resource in the Institute's educational infrastructure. Using that time for lectures — information delivery that a recording or text can do equally well — is waste. Using it for mentorship — the irreplaceable act of guided clinical reasoning in real time — is investment.</p>

      <div class="ped-highlight">
        <div class="ped-highlight-item waste">
          <div class="ped-highlight-header">
            <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"><line x1="18" y1="6" x2="6" y2="18"/><line x1="6" y1="6" x2="18" y2="18"/></svg>
            <span>Waste</span>
          </div>
          <p>Paying a senior clinician to stand in front of 40 students and explain pharmacokinetics. The same content delivered once on video reaches every student, can be paused, replayed, and studied at the student's own pace.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ped-highlight-item invest">
          <div class="ped-highlight-header">
            <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>
            <span>Investment</span>
          </div>
          <p>Paying that same clinician to sit with four students around a real patient case, guide their reasoning through the diagnostic complexity, challenge their formulation, and model the clinical thinking that only comes from decades of practice.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>The asynchronous component is not lesser. It is deliberately designed: reading, video modules, case preparation, reflective writing. The quality of synchronous mentorship depends entirely on the quality of asynchronous preparation. Students who arrive unprepared waste the mentorship that other students need.</p>
    </section>


    <!-- PORTFOLIO ASSESSMENT -->
    <section class="ped-section" id="portfolio-assessment">
      <div class="ped-section-label">Commitment III</div>
      <h2>Portfolio Assessment</h2>
      <p>The Institute does not use written examinations. Competency in complex therapeutic systems cannot be demonstrated by selecting the correct answer from four options under time pressure. It is demonstrated through accumulated evidence of clinical reasoning, reflective practice, and supervised outcomes over time.</p>

      <div class="portfolio-contents">
        <h3>What goes in the portfolio</h3>
        <div class="portfolio-grid">
          <div class="portfolio-item">
            <span class="portfolio-tag">Core</span>
            <h4>Case documentation</h4>
            <p>Every clinical encounter documented: assessment, formulation, intervention, outcomes, and follow-up. The longitudinal record of your clinical development.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="portfolio-item">
            <span class="portfolio-tag">Core</span>
            <h4>Reflective practice</h4>
            <p>Written reflection on clinical decisions, mistakes, surprises, and learning edges. What you didn't know, what you got wrong, and how your reasoning evolved.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="portfolio-item">
            <span class="portfolio-tag">External</span>
            <h4>Supervisor evaluations</h4>
            <p>Structured assessments from clinical mentors. Calibrated to tier-specific competency standards. Honest, detailed, and formative.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="portfolio-item">
            <span class="portfolio-tag">External</span>
            <h4>Peer review</h4>
            <p>Structured peer assessment of clinical reasoning and case management. Learning to evaluate others' clinical thinking is itself a competency.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>The portfolio doesn't end when the credential is granted. It becomes the ongoing record of professional development. CPD, case conferencing contributions, and protocol refinement all feed back into the same document. The portfolio is the practitioner's intellectual autobiography.</p>
    </section>


    <!-- CLINICAL TRAINING PIPELINE -->
    <section class="ped-section" id="clinical-pipeline">
      <div class="ped-section-label">Infrastructure</div>
      <h2>Clinical training pipeline</h2>
      <p>Sohma House functions as the Institute's teaching hospital. The relationship between clinical operations and education is not adjacent — it is integrated. Students learn within the same patient population that generates the Institute's research data and validates its clinical protocols.</p>

      <div class="pipeline-grid">
        <div class="pipeline-card">
          <h3>Patient population</h3>
          <p>Sohma House's active patient base provides the clinical complexity that training requires. Students don't practise on simulated patients or recruited volunteers. They work within an operational clinical practice serving real patients with real presentations.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-card">
          <h3>Calibrated autonomy</h3>
          <p>Student involvement scales with credential tier. Tier 1 observes and documents. Tier 2 assesses under supervision. Tier 3 manages with consultation. Fellows operate as junior clinicians with peer review. Every level has clear boundaries for patient safety.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-card">
          <h3>Data feedback loop</h3>
          <p>Clinical encounters generate outcome data that feeds into the Institute's research programs. The research generates protocols. The protocols are taught through education. The education trains practitioners who generate more clinical data. The loop is closed by design.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-card">
          <h3>Partner sites</h3>
          <p>As the practitioner network grows, approved partner clinical sites extend the training pipeline beyond Sohma House. Consistent standards, shared protocols, and standardised supervision frameworks ensure quality across all training locations.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- BACK -->
    <section class="ped-cta">
      <div class="cta-buttons">
        <a href="/education" class="cta-secondary">&larr; Back to Education Programs</a>
      </div>
    </section>

  </article>
</PortalLayout>

<style>
  .pedagogy-page {
    font-family: 'Manrope', sans-serif; color: var(--text-heading); padding: 0 clamp(24px, 4vw, 56px);
  }
  .pedagogy-page p { line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 1rem; }
  .pedagogy-page p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
  .pedagogy-page h1, .pedagogy-page h2, .pedagogy-page h3, .pedagogy-page h4 { margin: 0; }

  .section-label {
    display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1.25rem; font-size: 0.6875rem; font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.18em; color: var(--accent-dark); margin-bottom: 1rem; white-space: nowrap;
  }
  .section-label::after { content: ''; flex: 1; height: 1px; background: var(--accent-line); }

  /* ═══ HEADER ═══ */
  .ped-header { padding: 4rem 0 2.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }
  .page-title {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 4vw, 2.5rem);
    font-weight: 400; color: var(--text-heading); line-height: 1.2; margin-bottom: 1.75rem; letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  }
  .page-intro { font-size: 0.9375rem; color: var(--text-body-65); line-height: 1.85; max-width: 720px; }

  /* ═══ SECTIONS ═══ */
  .ped-section { padding-bottom: 3rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); margin-bottom: 3rem; }
  .ped-section-label {
    font-size: 0.5625rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    color: var(--accent-dark); margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }
  .ped-section h2 {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--text-heading); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.2;
  }
  .ped-section p { font-size: 0.9375rem; color: var(--text-body-70); line-height: 1.85; }

  /* Detail grid (3-col) */
  .ped-detail-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: 1rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
  .ped-detail { background: var(--bg-surface); border: 1px solid var(--border-light); border-radius: 6px; padding: 1.5rem; }
  .ped-detail h3 {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--text-heading); margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }
  .ped-detail p { font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-body-60); line-height: 1.7; }

  /* Highlight comparison */
  .ped-highlight { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 0; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
  .ped-highlight-item { padding: 1.75rem 1.5rem; }
  .ped-highlight-item.waste {
    background: var(--accent-hover-bg); border: 1px solid var(--accent-soft-10); border-radius: 6px 0 0 6px; border-right: none;
  }
  .ped-highlight-item.invest {
    background: rgba(104,124,87,0.05); border: 1px solid rgba(104,124,87,0.12); border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0;
    border-left: 1px solid var(--border-light);
  }
  .ped-highlight-header {
    display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .ped-highlight-header span {
    font-size: 0.6875rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  }
  .ped-highlight-item.waste .ped-highlight-header { color: var(--accent-soft-70); }
  .ped-highlight-item.invest .ped-highlight-header { color: var(--accent-green); }
  .ped-highlight-item p { font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.7; }

  /* Portfolio contents */
  .portfolio-contents { margin: 1.5rem 0; }
  .portfolio-contents h3 {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--text-heading); margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .portfolio-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .portfolio-item { background: var(--bg-surface); border: 1px solid var(--border-light); border-radius: 6px; padding: 1.25rem; }
  .portfolio-tag {
    display: inline-block; font-size: 0.5625rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--text-tertiary); border: 1px solid var(--border-medium); border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 2px 6px; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .portfolio-item h4 {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--text-heading); margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .portfolio-item p { font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-body-60); line-height: 1.7; }

  /* Pipeline grid */
  .pipeline-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); gap: 1rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
  .pipeline-card { background: var(--bg-surface); border: 1px solid var(--border-light); border-radius: 6px; padding: 1.5rem; }
  .pipeline-card h3 {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--text-heading); margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }
  .pipeline-card p { font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-body-60); line-height: 1.7; }

  /* CTA */
  .ped-cta { padding: 2rem 0 4rem; }
  .cta-buttons { display: flex; gap: 0.75rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .cta-secondary {
    font-size: 0.8125rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--glass-12); border-radius: 4px; padding: 12px 28px;
    text-decoration: none; transition: border-color 0.2s, color 0.2s;
  }
  .cta-secondary:hover { border-color: var(--accent-border-30); color: var(--accent-dark); }

  /* ═══ RESPONSIVE ═══ */
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .page-title { font-size: 1.75rem; }
    .ped-detail-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .ped-highlight { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .ped-highlight-item.waste { border-radius: 6px 6px 0 0; border-right: 1px solid var(--accent-soft-10); border-bottom: none; }
    .ped-highlight-item.invest { border-radius: 0 0 6px 6px; border-left: 1px solid rgba(104,124,87,0.12); }
    .portfolio-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .pipeline-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
</style>
